#Text=Wikinews interviews grassroots political advocate Anthony Maki
#Text=Wednesday , March 5 , 2008
#Text=Anthony Maki has hosted " get out the vote " caucus training sessions for students of Minnesota high schools .
#Text=In these sessions representatives of several presidential campaigns were present .
#Text=Mr. Maki has been interviewed by Jonathan Winterview for Wikinews .
#Text=Interview
#Text=( ( Wikinews ( Jonathon Winterview ) ) ) What are " get out the vote " caucus training sessions ?

#Text=Anthony Maki : " Get out the vote " drives and caucus training sessions lie at the heart of grassroots politics in the U. S. Also , in Minnesota , these are important facets of my state 's caucus procedures , which contrast with a majority of U. S. states that use only primaries .

#Text=My view is that " get out the vote " drives are specifically designed to target underrepresented minorities in the electorate , including but not limited to the youth , the working class poor , some elderly citizens , and racial minorities .
#Text=They accomplish two objectives : to register as many new voters as physically possible , and to inject a spirit of political and social awareness .
#Text=The ultimate goal is to create citizens who will continue , throughout their lives , to share their opinions and to be activists for their causes .
#Text=Getting out the vote has become increasingly easier to accomplish with the advent of mass media and especially the Internet .
#Text=Caucus trainings , while similar to getting out the vote , do have a different and equally important purpose .
#Text=For the states that use some sort of caucus procedures , these meetings , usually informal , explain the convoluted nature of caucuses .

#Text=The caucuses generally run on Robert 's Rules of Order , a system of formal and rule-based language intended to prevent any individual from wielding too much power and to eliminate time-consuming digressions .
#Text=The event that I organized was a hybrid of both and targeted high school students specifically , though some faculty members also attended .
#Text=We registered students , and I gave a presentation on the current candidates in multiple races and on the caucus procedures .
#Text=This was on 23 January , about two weeks in advance of Super Tuesday , in which Minnesota participated .

#Text=Given the apathetic archetype with which high school students are often dubbed , I think our turnout of approximately forty students in addition to about thirty more of faculty , the news media , the campaign representatives , etc. was spectacular .
#Text=One of the " get out the vote " sessions .
#Text=Another photo of the session .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) What do they aim to achieve ?
#Text=AM : Like I said before , these events and I as well are attempting to invigorate the populus in America about politics , and well , why not the world ?
#Text=Historically , my state has had high voter turnouts .
#Text=However , this is not the case in most other places of the world .
#Text=Too many people become resigned to the reality of politics in which they find themselves .
#Text=What I think they do not realize is that their resigned state can , in fact , facilitate the corruption and stagnation that we see everywhere .
#Text=It does not help to be apathetic .
#Text=These things try to be the antithesis .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) Do you think the sessions are successful in getting " underrepresented minorities " to vote ?
#Text=AM : Well , I certainly believe that it does .
#Text=Much of the work is publicizing it -- making voting and politics appealing .
#Text=That 's what I did .
#Text=I contacted the local news studios , like WCCO and KSTP , and the newspapers , the Minneapolis Star Tribune and the Anoka County Union .
#Text=It made quite a wave in the Minneapolis-Saint Paul metropolitan area .
#Text=All of the aforementioned media outlets put their stories online as well , so the circulation gets fairly large .
#Text=It 's almost as if inactive individuals are hiding . . . somewhere .
#Text=I make it my job to draw them out , to entice them , and so do many other activists everywhere .
#Text=As we have seen already , Senator Barack Obama has had great success with the youth and African-Americans .
#Text=Senator Hillary Clinton gets a lot of her support from union workers , Hispanics , and white women .
#Text=Out of all the groups I just mentioned , I would argue that the youth are the individuals most hidden .
#Text=They are either getting out in enormous numbers of their own accord , the efforts of people like me are helping , or some combination of both is at work .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) Have you been successful in encouraging people to register to vote ?
#Text=AM : I would like to think that I have contributed significantly to the registration of new voters , but it 's impossible for me to pinpoint a number .
#Text=Perhaps twenty people at the event I hosted registered there .
#Text=What this is really about is unification and cooperation between all of us citizens to educate and to motivate each other .
#Text=There are many other activists for which I may be a vague archetype , but I will not attempt to speak for them .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) What part has the Internet played in encouraging people to vote ?
#Text=AM : All of the media who covered my story put posts on their websites .
#Text=Those are permanent .
#Text=Ever since then , Googling my name has been a very interesting venture .
#Text=It seems as if there are bots that automatically syndicate stories to blog directories and other such portals .
#Text=Though none of this has attained what is called " viral " status , there is a viral quality in Internet stories .

column1: #Text=The contagiousness of the Internet allows individuals ' voices to permeate farther than they could have before , and in some cases , individuals can trump mass media conglomerations .
#Text=I think this is good , and it needs to continue .
#Text=I want to see an America with the opportunity for all to become candidates and to participate fully in our democracy .
#Text=Right now , I am not sure where America is at .
#Text=( ( WN ) ) Why do you consider it important to vote ?
#Text=AM : I want to effect change .
#Text=It 's as simple as that .
#Text=To effect change is to vote .
#Text=Of course , many other courses of action accompany this .
#Text=If you consider the time it takes to vote in a day , it 's really silly seeing some people not vote .
#Text=Then again , lately they have run out of ballots .
#Text=Simply put , nothing will change .
#Text=Unless you participate .
#Text=That goes for anyone in the world , not just the U. S. I think that it 's clear that people consider important .
#Text=At my city 's caucus site , more than seven times the usual number of people in a presidential election year turned out .
#Text=Gallery
